<DOC><DOCNO> AP890112-0264 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0647EST</FILEID><FIRST>d f BC-PhoneRefund     01-12 0155</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Phone Refund,0161</SECOND><HEAD>Pacific Bell Pays Out $94.5 Million In Penalties, Refunds</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Because of improper phone service charges,uncovered in a secret PUC probe, Pacific Bell has paid out $94.5million in penalties and refunds to 491,000 customers, the utilitysays.   Company officials said Tuesday $63 million in charges billed tocustomers for services they did not order or need were refundedbetween September 1986 and November 1988.   The utility spent another $15 million to notify 8.5 millioncustomers about the refunds, and yet another $16.5 million inpenalties levied by the Public Utilities Commission.   The PUC reported that an undercover staff investigation disclosedthat Pacific Bell representatives, among other things, often addedoptional features such as call-waiting and call-forwarding to billsalthough they hadn't been ordered.   The phone company said it will continue to offer the refunds tocustomers who received unwanted services between January 1985 andOctober 1986.</TEXT></DOC>